Here is a set or rules that was published on our server board that have been considered pretty reasonable: <br>
<br>
1. Expect to die. Raids are dangerous, and it is not unusual for someone to die 7 or 8 times in a successful raid. If the raid leaders are good, you will be rezzed, and this will not be a major problem. <br>
<br>
2. Expect to lose experience. Raids are not about gaining experience. They are about adventure and loot. If there are six groups in a raid, only one group will get any experience, and that experience may be outweighed by the experience loss from deaths. <br>
<br>
3. Expect to spend a lot of time doing nothing. Organizing a raid takes a lot of work, and you may sit around for hours while nothing happens, or while you are waiting for a rez. This is normal. Be patient. <br>
<br>
4. Do what you're told. The raid leaders don't have time to explain everything to every member of the raid, and they don't have time to debate tactics. Raids are not democratic. If the raid leader says, &quot;Go run up to Innoruuk and /rude him,&quot; just go do it. If you don't have faith in the raid leaders, you shouldn't be there. <br>
<br>
5. Shut up. In a large raid, things are chaotic. When people spam the zone in shout or ooc mode, it makes everything more difficult. Raids are not the time to show people how smart or funny you are. If you have questions or comments, use group mode or send a tell to a raid leader. <br>
<br>
6. Let the raid leaders deal with loot. Unless someone tells you to loot something, keep your hands off. <br>
<br>
7. Be prepared for a BIG time commitment. You can't expect to go to the Plane of Hate for two hours. If you don't have time to go on the raid, don't go at all. <br>
<br>
8. Assume that everything will take twice as long as it ought to. That may be conservative. <br>
<br>
9. Maintain a positive attitude, at least outwardly. No one wants to hear you whining or complaining or sniping at people. Everyone respects someone who maintains a &quot;can do&quot; attitude and who stays calm and rational even under bad circumstances. <br>
<br>
10. Pay attention. You'd be amazed how often people don't follow instructions. The raid leader will say &quot;No necromancer pets,&quot; and the necro will summon one anyway. Why does this happen? Because people aren't paying close attention to what is going on. They may be chatting in tells or in guild chat. I often turn off guild chat during raids, or at least ignore it unless someone says something directly to me. If someone sends me a tell, I may reply &quot;Not now&quot; or &quot;Let's talk later on, I'm on a raid.&quot; <br>
<br>
11. Don't be afraid to take a death for the good of the raid. There will be times when you are in imminent danger of death, but the only way you can save yourself will put the entire raid at risk. You have to control your impulse to run to safety, and just take the death. <br>
<br>
12. Prepare in advance so that you don't have to go AFK very often. Have your food and drink lined up. Take the dog for a walk. Finish your laundry. You just can't expect to go AFK very often on a raid. It is unreasonable to expect 40 people to wait around while you feed your cats. Make arrangements in advance whenever possible. (Yes, it is acceptable to take a bathroom break or to deal with a household emergency.) <br>
<br>
Thanks to Sagemon Prayeth for this information.<br>
