Keda has covered most of it. Those are the rules that most raids run by. I have just a little more to add though. <br>
<br>
For low level raids such as a lvl 40s 12 men thing, You can go to a few places that will actually prepare you for full plannar raids later on. <br>
<br>
Mock Fear: <br>
Trak's Teeth. I am surprised that no one suggest doing &quot;trail runs&quot; in Tracks teeth just to get a feel as to how a raid in Fear would be like. Of course it'll be scaled down but at lvl 40, TT can give you an indication of what's its going to be like. Lots of adds, aggros from all over and high lvl mobs that are about the same as those found in the planes. Built your &quot;co-ordination&quot; or raid awareness here. Its a good place to get xp, and good loot too. (go do the Forager Cycle) <br>
<br>
As for Hate, well.., I'd say invade Neriak but don't think your DE guildmates will like that too much. *grins* <br>
However, a Hole raid would be good. Thing is, at lvl 40+ ...the depeer mobs might be a tad too difficult for you guys. Though its another good place to learn how to co-ordinate a raid in an &quot;indoor&quot; enviroment (also has relatively good loot too for everyone ;IGS!!) <br>
<br>
There are dark sides to any raid of course, and that's when you need to keep and eye out. <br>
As an officer in my guild, I actually pay REALLY close attention during raids...for one thing, its when you can pin point the loot whores, the ones who don't show up for any other raid exept when they have something to gain or those who simply are detrimental to the guild. No one like whiners or those who creates dissent in the guild. A raid gone bad would be the best time to see just who are the ones working thier butts off to help thier friends and the ones freeloading. <br>
<br>
Last suggestions: <br>
ALWAYS have at least 2 backup raids planned incase the one you want is : <br>
1) taken by someone else, <br>
2) your key players aren't around / not enough of them. <br>
3) make sure everyone can get OUT of the raid area via ports / gates / potions / translocate. <br>
4)Make sure that how loot is going to be distributed and who will be calling the shots be made known in advance. Those who don't like and expect to roll for everything can take their sorry asre out the area.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
- Never, under any circumstansis, argue with the raid leader. The last thing they need is for you to cause a distraction. If you disagree with their raid makeup and strategy, leave during the briefing! or shut up and do as you're told. <br>
<br>
- Raids are more akin to military assualts than anything else but they are NOT a social ocassion. Have fun but stay focused!. <br>
<br>
- I can't stress this enough: KEEP YOUR COOL AT ALL TIMES. You may die if you keep your cool but you will certainly die if you panic -- and take a lot of folks with you. <br>
<br>
- Expect to die. <br>
<br>
- Expect to be told to do something that will mean your certain death. <br>
<br>
- Do NOT expect a rez. Ever. <br>
<br>
- Do NOT complain, grouse, or bitch. Period. If it takes 6hrs to get you rezed, deal with it. If you missed a roll on something for some reason, deal with it. Items are items they drop off mobs, friends don't and factions can't always be repaired. <br>
<br>
- LISTEN TO THE BRIEFING. If you have any questions in your mind about the assualt plan, the strategy used, the people assigned, etc, work them out or leave. Once the raid starts, shut the HELL up and deal with whatever happens, good or bad. The raid leader and management deserve your respect and 110% support once the raid begins. <br>
<br>
- Mistakes happen, we all make them. Never, ever, E V E R berate someone for making a mistake. It happens. Sometimes it causes wipeouts. They already feel bad and they dont' need your grief. <br>
<br>
- Listen to the minor stuff. Never let an order be issued twice because of YOU. &quot;Hug this wall&quot; isn't that hard to understand. <br>
<br>
- Raids are stressful, lighten the mood if you can. Last raid I didn't have an enchanter in my group (and everyone and his brother was asking for Clarity and even if it's your job after a few hours it can start to get on your nerves) so every time I had to ask I'd offer to preen his coat (he was in werewolf form), trading foraged grubs for clarity, oh most exaulted one I humbly beg for that most precious substance once again if you can perchance find your way clear to honor me for one brief moment, cough it up or I puke on your shoes, etc. <br>
<br>
- Everyone has bad days when nothing works, even gravity. Get over it. <br>
<br>
For as draconian as all that sounds, raids are fun if you keep your head, keep perspective, stay patient, follow instructions, and act like a mature adult. Even bad raids can be fun and challanging if you are focused on the journey and not on the loot.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Werzat's right, you should not &quot;expect&quot; an experience rez. Werzat's wrong, that rez should be lined up and ready to go, or the raid leader has failed a basic requirement. <br>
<br>
Both positions have a valid aspect. When you go on a raid, you should be able to rely on the leader to have adequate resources lined up to provide people with experience rezzes. At the same time, you should not take it for granted, and you should not &quot;expect&quot; that rez. <br>
<br>
Personally, I have some real problems keeping my happy face on while things are going to hell in a hand basket. I agree completely that you don't argue with the RL and you don't go along on the raid if the briefing includes things you find unacceptable. But when the &quot;briefing&quot; comes along somewhere well into the raid... grrr.. it's not exactly fair of a RL to not mention the rules until after people are physically committed, and it's kind of hard to get the rules out of a reluctant RL without it coming off like arguing. <br>
<br>
I've been on a raid where the CR was so long and slow that by the time they got my corpse, it was too old for an experience resurrection. That was an aggravating and frustrating experience, because I was kept uninformed about what was happening and was not in a position to do anything except sit and wait and stew. Things can, do and will turn out badly sometimes, and despite the best intentions and reasonable preparations, a raider may find that there is no exp. rez. Unfortunate, but a risk in the game. <br>
<br>
It's been said again and again before, but cannot be overemphasized - <br>
listen to the Raid Leader's instructions and follow them to the letter. [ If you know the zone inside out and the RL just said &quot;hug the right wall&quot; and you know (and know the RL knows even) that it has to be the LEFT wall, send a tell letting them know they oopsed. But Do Not make that announcement/correction for them in shout or ooc.. it will only confuse things.] <br>
Pay attention.. you can't follow instructions if you aren't paying attention, you can't catch a correction if you aren't paying attention, etc. etc. etc. <br>
<br>
Something that wasn't mentioned... if you are going on a raid, be prepared, do your homework. Be On Time for the raid... that means being at the announced starting point before the announced starting time if humanly possible. It means having a key for the zone if one is needed. It means having appropriate resistance gear. It means having the tooth to port to Cobalt Scar if you're going to Western Wastes. It means having the zone loaded on your machine if you're going to The Hole. <br>
<br>
And yes, I've sat and waited for people joining raids in The Hole who turned out not to have it loaded. I've sat and waited for people going on raids in WW who could not be ported into Cobalt Scar. I even know of a person who signed up for a Hate Raid and had a hissy fit about being deliberately left behind at the wizard platform.. when they were level 45... <br>
<br>
<br>
So.. be considerate and cooperative and follow instructions. That pretty well covers it, but it's amazing how hard people find it to do these simple things.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
All of the suggestions up top are great. I would just like to add some more. <br>
<br>
1) Always keep your cool - it really is surprising what can be pulled off if people don't panic. Having 5-8 mobs in camp with the enchanter out of mana, the cleric with 20% left. It tests everyone and they seem to fight at their best. Like I said - very fun =) <br>
<br>
2) Unless something is stated otherwise - mash that Assist key. Nothing will piss off an enchanter faster and make the entire raid proceed slower. <br>
<br>
3) Always respect the chain of command. I don't know how your guild is setup - but on raids I lead I want absolute authority. I do not want tells telling me what I should be doing. A good leader has already done his homework and knows what to do. <br>
<br>
4) Loot plan needs to be discussed prior to going. Discuss as it drops gets messy and slows down things. <br>
<br>
5) Just have fun - and make sure the people there are at least trying to have fun. Some raids are very boring, but are necessary to do. Remember to try to balance experience no matter if people say they are not interested in experience - because they really are. <br>
<br>
CoM is a very good starter guild raid. It is fairly easy to do corpse recovery. For good execution runs, I suggest the Hole. It has a fairly fast repop - fairly low level mobs and requires some homework. It is also the easiest zone to do corpse recovery in. <br>
<br>
Enjoy. <br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Here are some rules for raids, if you are not the leader: <br>
<br>
1. Show up, on time, prepared (equipment, maps, resist gear, potions, gems for symbols, fish scales, coffins, etc)). <br>
2. Join the group you are assigned. <br>
3. Be helpful: Buff others (but ask them first). <br>
4. Follow instructions. <br>
5. DO NOT EXPLORE or wander. Stay with the group or in your assigned place. <br>
6. Before raid starts, determine the following and make hotkeys: <br>
- primary assist hotkey <br>
- secondary assist hotkey <br>
- &quot;add&quot; assist hotkey <br>
- special raid hotkeys (&quot;Assist Locz on %t&quot;, &quot;Snared %t&quot;, &quot;Peeling %t&quot;, &quot;Parking %t, back off!&quot;, &quot;Incoming %t&quot;, &quot;%t has been slowed&quot;, &quot;Kiting %t&quot;, etc). <br>
- determine the raid-only channel for instructions <br>
- determine the &quot;chat&quot; channel <br>
- name of loot leader <br>
- name of enchanter giving haste <br>
- name of enchanter giving clarity <br>
- name of persons giving focus / DMF / aegiolism / etc <br>
7. get buffed in the proper buff order (junk and lesser buffs first) <br>
8. LISTEN to instructions. <br>
19. FOLLOW instructions. <br>
10. Don't harass the raid leader / puller / peeler / assist people with tells. They are too busy. <br>
11. Don't whine about experience. The purpose of a raid is not experience (thats a &quot;grind&quot; group). Groups are specifically arranged to maximize kill effectiveness, not for divvying up experience evenly. <br>
12. Don't loot unless told to. <br>
13. When fighting: <br>
- follow instructions. <br>
- always assist. Never attack unless you assist. (take personal initiative only when assists have died and announce to others your action using a hotkey / you are told otherwise / dire circumstances require it). <br>
- don't sit just before the pull (MOB may aggro you). <br>
- turn off auto-attack if the MOB enrages. (enrage = autoriposte) <br>
- usually best to keep the chanter's alive (it is OK to emergency heal them) <br>
- learn to &quot;push&quot; caster/healer MOBs so that their casting gets interrupted. This means all tanks but rogues fight on the same side and vector, pushing the MOB backwards, and switch sides as told by the main assist. This technique also makes the raid rogues far more effective. <br>
- avoid aggroing secondary MOBs into the fight. <br>
- only the raid leader calls for &quot;clerics camp&quot; if a wipeout seems possible. <br>
- announce specifically important events: key LDs, key deaths, MOB AE cast times, snare in, emergency heal needs (if your clerics are dead). <br>
- casters only nuke within aggro radius, and after the tanks have secured aggro, to avoid &quot;ping ponging&quot; <br>
- don't push the MOB through a wall, or off a bridge, etc. <br>
14. Group leaders announce mana level /preparedness after the fight. <br>
15. NEVER, EVER, train the camp. Die instead. <br>
<br>
Hope this summarizes well. <br>
